Description: The U.S.S.R. achieved a rendezvous with a distance of several kilometers, and had radio contact between two Vostok crafts. However, no formation flying was possible. In this mission, you will rendezvous with another Gemini spacecraft, and fly in formation with it using the OAMS thursters.

MissionCommands.Message: Good morning, {{profileName}}, this is CapCom! This will most likely be one of the hardest missions yet, you guys all ready and set up?
Good morning, Paul! Yes, we are all strapped in and the cockpit is almost ready for flight.
Roger. Just had a word with Commander Patrick. I think they are eager to see another face after a week in orbit. He also wanted me to let you know that they completed 3 "firsts", whatever that means.
Roger, I can imagine they did. Let's get this spaceship up there!
Sounds like a plan, proceed with the Pre-Flight checklist and report when ready.
Ok, we should be good to go. {{profileName}}, verify platform alignment, we should be targeting an inclination of 28.91 degrees.
Roger, will verify FDAI. Roll program programmed to {{valueInCore_Value3}}.
Verfiy cockpit is ready, and prepare for launch.
T-60 seconds, you know the drill.
T-30 seconds!
Bolts and liftoff!
Roger liftoff!
Seems like we have lost battery 1?
Really? Ok, let's see what we got here. Houston, we seem to have lost battery 1, can you verify?
{{capsuleName}}, we are seeing the same. Digging into the data, but proceed for now, focus on the ascent. {{coPilotName}}, keep an eye on the electrical system.
Roger. {{coPilotName}}, start with checking the other batteries and squibs. All good?
They seem good. Let's keep them on during ascent, then turn them off after insertion. We can complete the entry with only 3 batteries.
Roger, proceeding ascent.
We have staging, all good.
Roger, we see the same.
EPS looking good after separation.
Roger, that's good.
Such as beautiful sight, can't get tired of this.
Agree, one of the benefits of space flight!
Exactly, but this tight space is not. Wonder how Patrick and Matthew are doing in orbit. Imagine spending two weeks here.
Yeah, but they sure get a lot of time in space on their records.
Curious on how it will be to fly in the Apollo program, hope to get the chance to fly it.
Oh yes, I'm sure there will be a good chance for that after completing these missions.
Ok, it got silent in here, we have SECO.
Roger SECO.
Alright, let's separate from that launch vehicle.
Separating from the LV. It was a good ride.
Jettison the fairings and zero the IVI's. Press DONE when ready.
Perform the post insertion checklist. We are working on the Orbit Circularization Maneuver. Standby.
Roger.
Let's hope the other batteries get back online for our retrograde burn and reentry.
I'm sure they will.
Is the CATCH-UP computer module running?
Catch-Up module running.
Ok, we are uplinking an OBC update with the target parameters of the new circular orbit. The burn will take place at Pe in about {{timeToPe}}.
Roger, circularization burn scheduled for the next Pe passing, in about {{timeToPe}}.
Verify the OBC cores and reference the Circularize Orbit checklist, and bring this craft into a circular orbit.
We are getting into a circular orbit.
When ready and the orbit is circular and aligned to 28.91 degrees inclination, call the REQUEST TARGET BURN radio command.
Program the computer so your target orbit for the burn is aligned with Gemini. Set Core #57 so its the same as Core #81. Then set Core #56 so its equal to Core #80. Reference the checklist.
We are {{timeToTransferBurn}} from the initial transfer burn. Ensure you are in SEF attitude, burn will be in prograde direction.
One minute. Precision is key, good luck!
BURN, zero the IVIs!
Setting radar to Standby.
The radar needs 5 minutes to warm up and prepare.
The radar is ready, set it to ON.
This will automatically lock on Gemini when we are in range. We will arrive in {{timeToAp}}.
Roger, let's hope the burn will take us there!
We are still coasting. Time to final burn is {{timeToAp}}.
50 seconds to burn. Align to SEF and get ready for the burn.
Ok, here we go, zero the IVIs when ready, and press DONE after the burn.
Done!
Roger, setting computer to RNDZ. It needs 10 minutes to load.
Change the FDAI1 source to RDR, and the FDAI1 Display to ATT. Follow the FDAI pointer to point towards the target. Use the radar and try to get within 10k feet from the target.
Use the radar to get closer to the target.
Starboard: {{capsuleName}}, this is Starboard and Commander {{Patrick}}, do you read?
Loud and clear, Patrick!
Starboard: Sounds good, let's see how close we can get.
Try to get within 300 feet from the target.
Starboard: It sure is great to see you up here {{profileName}}, did you imagine this would happen back in the Academy?
Definitely not! This is amazing!
Starboard: We sure could need a walk, been here for 7 days already.
Hope you are enjoing the mission and the spacecraft, sure is an amazing machine!
Starboard: Oh yes, this is a proper spacecraft!
Let's get closer and try to fly in formation
Excellent work! Spend some time in close proximity and try to get a feel of the craft and the impact of the thrusters.
Roger, will do.
Starboard: This is awesome. Highlight of my career!
You are right about that!
Ok, primary objectives has been met. Excellent piloting all, and it's time for {{capsuleName}} to return home
Roger. Will bring the craft down. (Mission Complete: You can optionally return the craft home)

Title: FACE TO FACE
